        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-05-13T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-05-13T13:00:00-05:00" n="1347" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1347">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.9376/5–749: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Tientsin</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Smyth</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="60" xml:id="d1347fn60">Repeated to the Consul General at
                        Peiping as No. 278.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-05-13T14:00:00-04:00">May 13, 1949—2 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>98. Dept perceives no objection as general rule to Consuls in Commie areas
                    addressing Commie authorities by letter signed either in personal capacity or
                    over official title (urtel 292 May 7 repeated Nanking 183, Peiping 125), but
                    such authorities shld be addressed personally by name without inclusion official
                    titles. However Dept believes that where circumstances permit it preferable
                    communicate by means memoranda (either unsigned, initialed, or signed with or
                    without consular title) delivered appropriate Commie authorities by consular
                    officers.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
